description.narrative: Minimize the adverse effects of transnational threats and criminal activities on the United States and its citizens, particularly when these activities involve cross-border connections or have cross-border effects. Promote international cooperation and coordination, and provide training and other technical assistance to help build institutional capacity for combating transnational threats including those to cybersecurity and international criminal activities such as corruption, alien smuggling, financial crimes (including money laundering), violations of intellectual property law, and cybercrime.

Support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy, most importantly financial intermediation – the efficient generation and allocation of savings to their most productive use.

This award strives to minimize the adverse effects of transnational threats and criminal activies on the United States and its citizens, particularly when these activities involve cross-border connections or have cross-border effects. More specifically, this includes Provide expert consultation to the Eastern Caribbean Central Bank (ECCB) to support its supervision of the domestic banking sector in the eight countries within the Eastern Caribbean Currency Union (ECCU) that fall under its jurisdiction aimed at developing (i) consistent supervision practices by the ECCB across the eight ECCU countries, notwithstanding varying legal frameworks and capacity; (ii) risk-based supervision practices, consistent with international standards; (iii) the capacity of examiners to perform off- and on-site examinations applying updated supervision tools and skills; (iv) mechanisms to coordinate with anti-money laundering and countering the financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) stakeholders in each jurisdiction; and (v) designing and conducting outreach activities to engage the domestic banking sectors.. Provide expert consultation to the Eastern Caribbean Central Bank (ECCB) to support its supervision of the domestic banking sector in the eight countries within the Eastern Caribbean Currency Union (ECCU) that fall under its jurisdiction aimed at conducting (i) gap assessments of compliance by ECCU jurisdictions with international anti-money laundering and countering the financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) standards; (ii) risk assessments, whether at a regional, national or institutional level; (iii) risk-based onsite and offsite supervision; and (iv) training and market sensitization. These activities are aimed at developing consistent supervision practices by the ECCB across the eight ECCU countries, notwithstanding varying legal frameworks and capacity.. Provide expert consultation to the Eastern Caribbean Central Bank (ECCB) to support its supervision of the domestic banking sector in the eight countries within the Eastern Caribbean Currency Union (ECCU) that fall under its jurisdiction, to include (a) developing ECCB approach to AML/CFT supervision for institutions licensed under the Banking Act, providing for the application of consistent supervision across the eight countries under ECCB authority which vary in legal and regulatory requirements; (b) improving ECCB capacity to conduct off- and onsite AML/CFT supervision, especially in the area of the development and review of off- and onsite examination processes and tools; (c) mentoring ECCB examiners during off- and onsite AML/CFT examination of a regulated entity in St. Vincent and the Grenadines to underscore practical implementation of processes and tools; (d) developing ECCB mechanisms to coordinate with AML/CFT stakeholders in each ECCU country; and (e) establishing ECCB AML/CFT outreach activities to regulated entities.. Assist the ECCB to develop consistent AML/CFT supervision practices across the eight jurisdictions, notwithstanding varying legal frameworks and capacity; develop risk-based AML/CFT supervision practices, consistent with international standards; develop the capacity of its examiners to perform AML/CFT off- and on-site examinations applying updated supervision tools and skills; develop mechanisms to coordinate with AML/CFT stakeholders in each jurisdiction; and design and conduct outreach activities to engage the domestic banking sectors.. Provide expert consultation to the Eastern Caribbean Central Bank (ECCB) to support its supervision of the domestic banking sector in the eight countries within the Eastern Caribbean Currency Union (ECCU) that fall under its jurisdiction, to include (1) developing ECCB approach to anti-money laundering and countering the financing of terrorism (AML/CFT) supervision for institutions licensed under the Banking Act, providing for the application of consistent supervision across the eight countries under ECCB authority which vary in legal and regulatory requirements; (2) improving ECCB capacity to conduct off- and onsite AML/CFT supervision, especially in the area of the development and review of off- and onsite examination processes and tools; (3) mentoring ECCB examiners during off- and onsite AML/CFT examination of a regulated entity in St. Vincent and the Grenadines (SVG) to underscore practical implementation of processes and tools; (4) developing ECCB mechanisms to coordinate with AML/CFT stakeholders in each ECCU country; and (5) establishing ECCB AML/CFT outreach activities to regulated entities.. Assist the Eastern Caribbean Central Bank (ECCB) to develop consistent AML/CFT supervision practices across the eight jurisdictions that fall under the domestic banking supervisory authority of the ECCB, notwithstanding varying legal frameworks and capacity; develop risk-based AML/CFT supervision practices, consistent with international standards; develop the capacity of ECCB examiners to perform AML/CFT off- and on-site examinations applying updated supervision tools and skills; develop mechanisms to coordinate with AML/CFT stakeholders in each of the eight jurisdictions; and design and conduct outreach activities to engage the domestic banking sectors.. Project is closed. Project is closed..
